Select and SelectMany are LINQ extension methods that allow you to transform elements in a sequence.

Select is used to project each element of a sequence into a new form, such as selecting specific properties of an object. In LINQ to SQL, you can use Select to select specific columns of a database table and create a new sequence of anonymous types with those columns.

Here's an example:

csharp

using (var db = new MyDataContext())
{
    var query = from customer in db.Customers
                select new { customer.FirstName, customer.LastName };

    foreach (var item in query)
    {
        Console.WriteLine("{0} {1}", item.FirstName, item.LastName);
    }
}

SelectMany is used to flatten a sequence of sequences into a single sequence. In LINQ to SQL, you can use SelectMany to select multiple columns from multiple tables and create a new sequence of anonymous types with those columns.

Here's an example:

csharp

using (var db = new MyDataContext())
{
    var query = from customer in db.Customers
                from order in customer.Orders
                select new { customer.FirstName, customer.LastName, order.OrderDate };

    foreach (var item in query)
    {
        Console.WriteLine("{0} {1} - {2}", item.FirstName, item.LastName, item.OrderDate);
    }
}

In this example, the SelectMany method is used to flatten the sequence of orders for each customer into a single sequence of anonymous types with customer first and last names and order date.

